  "notes": [
    {
      "title": "Plural Demonstratives",
      "titleArabic": "أسماء الإشارة للجمع",
      "content": [
        "Arabic uses specific demonstrative pronouns for plurals. Unlike singular demonstratives which distinguish masculine and feminine, plural demonstratives use one form for both genders.",
        "The demonstrative هَؤُلَاءِ (these) refers to nearby plural nouns, while أُولَئِكَ (those) refers to distant plural nouns."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "هَؤُلَاءِ - these (for all plurals, near)",
        "أُولَئِكَ - those (for all plurals, far)",
        "Both are مبني (indeclinable) - their endings don't change",
        "Used for both masculine and feminine plurals"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "هَؤُلَاءِ طُلَّابٌ", "english": "These are students" },
        { "arabic": "أُولَئِكَ مُدَرِّسُونَ", "english": "Those are teachers" },
        { "arabic": "هَؤُلَاءِ النِّسَاءُ طَبِيبَاتٌ", "english": "These women are doctors" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Review of Demonstrative System",
      "titleArabic": "مراجعة أسماء الإشارة",
      "content": [
        "The complete demonstrative system in Arabic includes singular, dual, and plural forms for both near and far references."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Singular near: هَذَا (m.), هَذِهِ (f.)",
        "Singular far: ذَلِكَ (m.), تِلْكَ (f.)",
        "Dual near: هَذَانِ (m.), هَاتَانِ (f.)",
        "Plural near/far: هَؤُلَاءِ / أُولَئِكَ"
      ]
    }
  ],
